          "text": "<teammate-message teammate_id=\"reviewer-minltl\" color=\"yellow\" summary=\"MinLTL.v review complete: all clean, no issues\">\n## MinLTL.v Review — Complete\n\n### Compilation\nSuccessfully compiles with Coq 8.19.2 (via `nix develop`). No warnings or errors.\n\n### Admitted / admit / Abort\n**None found.** All 30+ proofs close with `Qed`. The file is fully proven.\n\n### Axiom Review (9 temporal axioms from the paper + novel axioms)\n\nAll 9 paper axioms are correctly stated:\n\n| # | Name | Statement | Verdict |\n|---|------|-----------|---------|\n| 1 | `next_not` | ◯ ¬p ≈ ¬◯ p | Standard self-duality of Next. Correct. |\n| 2 | `next_impl` | ◯ (p ⇒ q) ≈ ◯ p ⇒ ◯ q | Standard distributivity of Next over ⇒. Correct. |\n| 9 | `next_until` | ◯ (p U q) ≈ ◯ p U ◯ q | Distributivity of Next over Until. Correct. |\n| 10 | `until_expand` | p U q ≈ q ∨ (p ∧ ◯ (p U q)) | Standard expansion/fixpoint law. Correct. |\n| 11 | `until_false` | p U ⊥ ⟹ ⊥ | Right zero of Until. Correct. |\n| 12 | `until_left_or` | p U (q ∨ r) ≈ (p U q) ∨ (p U r) | Left distributivity of U over ∨. Correct. |\n| 14 | `until_left_and` | p U (q ∧ r) ⟹ (p U q) ∧ (p U r) | Left distributivity of U over ∧ (one direction, as expected). Correct. |\n| 17 | `until_left_or_order` | p U (q U r) ⟹ (p ∨ q) U r | Right U-∨ ordering. Correct. |\n| 18 | `until_right_and_order` | p U (q ∧ r) ⟹ (p U q) U r | Right ∧-U ordering. Correct. |\n| 170 | `not_until` | ⊤ U ¬p ∧ ¬(p U q) ≈ ¬q U (¬p ∧ ¬q) | Negation of Until (dual characterization). Correct. |\n\n**Novel axioms:**\n\n- **`looped`** (◯ ¬p U p ⟹ p): This is the well-foundedness/anti-loop axiom. Semantically: if ¬p holds at each next step until p eventually holds (via strong Until), then p must hold now — otherwise you get an infinite regress where p is always deferred. This is sound in standard LTL over infinite traces because strong Until requires the eventuality to be fulfilled. Reasonable and necessary to prevent degenerate models.\n\n- **`until_and_until`** ((p U q) ∧ (r U s) ⟹ (p ∧ r) U ((q ∧ r) ∨ (p ∧ s) ∨ (q ∧ s))): Combines two Until formulas. The three disjuncts correctly capture the three cases: q arrives first (while r still holds), s arrives first (while p still holds), or both arrive simultaneously. Standard LTL result. Correct.\n\n### Module Structure\n- `MinimalLinearTemporalLogic` module type properly extends `BooleanLogic` via `Include BooleanLogic`.\n- `MinimalLinearTemporalLogicFacts` functor correctly parameterized over `MinimalLinearTemporalLogic`.\n- Imports `BooleanLogicFacts` and `MinimalBooleanLogicFacts` correctly.\n\n### Proper Instances\n- `next_respects_implies` and `until_respects_implies` correctly declared as axioms in the module type.\n- `next_respects_equivalent` and `until_respects_equivalent` correctly derived as `Program Instance` in the Facts module using the `one_arg`/`two_arg` obligation tactics.\n- This enables full setoid rewriting support for both operators.\n\n### Proof Quality\n- **Clean and well-structured.** All proofs follow the equational reasoning style.\n- **Good tactic usage:** Effective use of `boolean`, `rewrite`, `reflexivity`, `now`, and `apply`.\n- **Excellent documentation:** Comments at lines 78–87 and 150–179 map theorem numbers to descriptions from the paper.\n- **Clear labeling:** Paper theorems marked with numbers (e.g., `(* 13 *)`), novel results marked `(* NEW *)`.\n- **Concise but readable proofs** — most are 2–6 lines.\n\n### Operator Precedence\nChecked the parsing of `not_until` (line 58): `⊤ U ¬p ∧ ¬(p U q) ≈ ¬q U (¬p ∧ ¬q)`. Since ∧ binds tighter than U (level 79 vs ∧ at ~80), the LHS parses as `(⊤ U ¬p) ∧ ¬(p U q)`. This matches the paper's formulation of theorem 170.\n\n### Issues Found\n**None.** The file is in excellent shape — fully proven, correctly axiomatized, well-documented, and compiles cleanly.\n</teammate-message>",
